nwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Eldwolde was born in 1475, in Badingham, Suffolk, England. She married Robert D. Derehaugh about 1489, in Bruisyard, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. She died on 21 April 1524, in her hometown, at the age of 49, and was buried in Badingham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1475–21 April 1524":"1475–21. aprill 1524","1473–1524":"1473–1524","1490–1553":"1490–1553","1507–Female":"1507–Surnud","1515–1553":"1515–1553","–1557":"–1557","1475–1524":"1475–1524","about 1507":"umbes 1507","1557":"1557","1524":"1524","1553":"1553","1475":"1475","1473":"1473","about 1489":"umbes 1489","1507":"1507","1490":"1490","1515":"1515","April 1524":"aprill 1524","21 April 1524":"21. aprill 1524","Bruisyard, Badingham, Suffolk, England":"Bruisyard, Suffolk, England","Badingham, Suffolk, England":"Badingham, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Sibton, Suffolk, England":"Sibton, Suffolk, England","Badingham, Suffolk Coastal District, Suffolk, England":"Badingham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","St John the Baptist Churchyard, Badingham, Suffolk, England":"Badingham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bruisyard, Suffolk, England":"Bruisyard, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1475–21 April 1524":"1475–21. huhtikuuta 1524","1473–1524":"1473–1524","1490–1553":"1490–1553","1507–Female":"1507–Kuollut","1515–1553":"1515–1553","–1557":"–1557","1475–1524":"1475–1524","about 1507":"noin 1507","1557":"1557","1524":"1524","1553":"1553","1475":"1475","1473":"1473","about 1489":"noin 1489","1507":"1507","1490":"1490","1515":"1515","April 1524":"huhtikuu 1524","21 April 1524":"21. huhtikuuta 1524","Bruisyard, Badingham, Suffolk, England":"Bruisyard, Suffolk, England","Badingham, Suffolk, England":"Badingham, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Sibton, Suffolk, England":